<h2><a name='sect8' href='#toc8'>Description</a></h2>
<p>
C]MPI_File_write_ordered_endR]
is the ending part of a split collective routine that must be called by
all processes in the communicator group associated with the file handle
C]fhR]. C]MPI_File_write_ordered_endR] returns the number of elements written
into the file associated with C]fhR] in C]statusR].
<h2><a name='sect9' href='#toc9'>Notes</a></h2>
<p>
All the nonblocking
collective routines for data access are [lq]split[rq] into two routines,
each with _begin or _end as a suffix. These split collective routines are
subject to the semantic rules described in Section 9.4.5 of the MPI-2 standard.

<h2><a name='sect10' href='#toc10'>Errors</a></h2>
<p>
Almost all MPI routines return an error value; C routines as the
value of the function and Fortran routines in the last argument. <p>
Before
the error value is returned, the current MPI error handler is called. For
MPI I/O function errors, the default error handler is set to C]MPI_ERRORS_RETURNR].
The error handler may be changed with C]MPI_File_set_errhandlerR]; the
predefined error handler C]MPI_ERRORS_ARE_FATALR] may be used to make I/O
errors fatal. Note that MPI does not guarantee that an MPI program can continue
past an error. <p>

